Two cuts from the same individual foraging in a pine at the parking lot about 15-20ft above ground.

A Carolina Chickadee—probably a female, possibly trying to get to a nearby nest hole—calls repeatedly from one of several perches at eye level and close. A male can be heard singing in the distance in the background. Background also includes: a Cerulean Warbler singing away. Recorded using a Fostex FR-2LE with a Sennheiser ME62 & Telinga Universal 22" parabola.

Locality: New River Gorge NP--Fern Creek, Endless Wall N Trailhead
Media notes: Song and brief calls from a bird at dawn.
Nice example of the chick-a-dee-dee-dee-dee calls typical for this area.

Early morning song and conversation between the 2 Chickadees.  Near the end of this recording, one of the Carolina Chickadees was atop his nest box singing loudly.  There can also be heard Northern Cardinal, Carolina Wren, human (me) walking, wind sounds, and American Robin towards the end.  Giving these birds their space as they are breeding.  Not getting too close to the nest box area but still a beautiful song.
Observation Details: Chickadees have taken up in a nest box here.  In the early morning, one bird sings to the one in the box and they call back and forth
